Double Robustness

Rachael Caelie (Rocky) Aikens

4/10/2020

Double Robustness and Fisher Mill

I’ve been thinking a little about a visualization for double robustnesss. Let’s consider a data generating process much like our usual: \[\begin{align*} X_i &\sim_{iid} \text{Normal}(0,I_p),\\ T_i &\sim_{iid} \text{Bernoulli}\left(\frac{1}{1+\exp(-\phi(X_i))}\right),\\ Y_i &=\tau T_i + \Psi(X_i) + \epsilon_i,\\ \epsilon_i &\sim_{iid} N(0,\sigma^2), \end{align*}\] Except that the true propensity score now depends on two variables: \(X_1\) and \(X_3\), \[\begin{align*} \phi(X_i) &= X_{i1}/3-c,\\ \Psi(X_i) &=\rho X_{i1} + \sqrt{(1-\rho^2)}X_{i2}, \end{align*}\]
